[cols=",,,",]
|===
|[.s1]#*Phase*# |[.s1]#*Component*# |[.s1]#*Brief Description*#
|[.s1]#*Mechanism / UEFI Protocol*#

|[.s1]#*Preparation*# |[.s1]#*GPT Partitioning*# |[.s1]#The disk must
use a GUID Partition Table. The bootloader lives in the EFI System
Partition (ESP).# |[.s1]#Hardware Standard (GPT); FAT32 filesystem.#

|[.s1]#*Entry*# |[.s1]#*EFI Main*# |[.s1]#The entry point of the
loader. It will receive a "Handle" to the image and a pointer to the
"System Table."# |[.s1]#EFI++_++STATUS efi++_++main(EFI++_++HANDLE
image, EFI++_++SYSTEM++_++TABLE ++*++sys)#

|[.s1]#*System Info*# |[.s1]#*Memory Map*# |[.s1]#UEFI maintains a much
more detailed memory map than BIOS. The bootloader "exit boot services" 
later to own it.# |[.s1]#GetMemoryMap() via Boot Services.#

|[.s1]#*Graphics*# |[.s1]#*GOP (Graphics Output)*# |[.s1]#UEFI does not
use VGA. It must request a pointer to the linear framebuffer to draw
pixels.# |[.s1]#EFI++_++GRAPHICS++_++OUTPUT++_++PROTOCOL#

|[.s1]#*File Access*# |[.s1]#*Simple File System*# |[.s1]#It does not need
to write a FAT32 driver; the firmware already has one. It just "Open"
the kernel file.#
|[.s1]#EFI++_++SIMPLE++_++FILE++_++SYSTEM++_++PROTOCOL#

|[.s1]#*Kernel Prep*# |[.s1]#*Memory Allocation*# |[.s1]#it must
allocate specific memory pages for the kernel segments.#
|[.s1]#AllocatePages() with AllocateAddress.#

|[.s1]#*The Hand-off*# |[.s1]#*Exit Boot Services*# |[.s1]#*CRITICAL:*
This shuts down firmware drivers and gives the kernel 100% control of
the CPU.# |[.s1]#ExitBootServices()#

|[.s1]#*Transition*# |[.s1]#*Virtual Mapping*# |[.s1]#(Optional but
common) UEFI runs in identity-mapped long mode; it may set up its own
page tables here.# |[.s1]#MOV CR3, ++<++table++_++address++>++#

|[.s1]#*Handoff*# |[.s1]#*Final Jump*# |[.s1]#Since UEFI is already in
64-bit (or 32-bit) mode, it simply cast your kernel address to a
function pointer.# |[.s1]#((void
(++*++)(BOOT++_++Info++*++))kernel++_++entry)(s++_++bootInfo);#
|===
